cID=411.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: *ooc* Have the tissues ready...</span><hr size=1> Very touching Prav, thank you for sharing it.   Do you mind if I print it out and bring it to work?<br>
<br>
As most of you know, I am an EMT, what most of you guys don't know, is that because I work for the fire department, I am also technically a fire fighter, and every now and then, I do get to employ those skills as well.  <br>
<br>
I personally knew some of the fire fighters lost that day.  I worked with some of them, trained with them, cried with them.  Several of them recieved their initial training through the fire department volunteer program my city runs, and they still came all this way down to volunteer their 24 hours a month, though their contracts required for the &quot;free&quot; training had cleared them of the obligations often years before.  I live in a military area, and these people served in the military, became fire fighters/EMT's, then got out and moved to New York.   True American heros.  There entire life was a sacrifice so that the rest of us might live in freedom and the safety of knowing that there are people out there that will save their lives if tragedy falls upon them.  <br>
<br>
Many of the fire fighters lost that day were NOT carreer fire fighters.   There were many volunteers lost that day as well.  They had carreers elsewhere, offering only hours each month, or serving in times of crisis.  They were NOT paid to do what they did, they volunteered their time.  Though I'm carreer now, my own &quot;roots&quot; lie with the volunteer services.<br>
<br>
Another thing most people don't realize is that for most of the month of september, our fire department was basically run by volunteers, because many of us, myself included responded to the tragedy in New York.  I saw many things up there that I don't ever want to see again.   The destruction and loss of life that day is still an inconceivable thought.  But I also saw hope up there.  I saw people with no medical or rescue knowledge whatsoever standing there, ready to hold the hand of a complete stranger to offer comfort.  So many people willing to lend a hand in any way they could. All of the sudden, in a time of dispair, people from all over pulling together to help overcome tragedy.  In the moment of greatest dispair, a new hope was born in New York.  <br>
<br>
OK that's enough rambling for me.  (and Yes, I am crying as I write this.  That email could easily have been a little girl of someone I know and work with.  It could easily have been one of my children.) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#8E236B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/upravdameer.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Pravdameer</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Dread Overlord</span><br>  Posts: 148<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/16/02 10:56:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/fvhbrellfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=411.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: *ooc* Have the tissues ready...</span><hr size=1> *smile* Thank you for sharing that, Natori, and by all means - print it out and share it. I make no claim to ownership, but the copy I recieved asked me to pass it along to those I know - I chose posting to some boards rather than email, and I see no difference in printing it out and sharing as well. <p>Pravdameer Pravdamorte<br>
